European inflation has shifted in food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the vertigious growth in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the EU Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely to give a 3 percent - the Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "there is a need to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene later on.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, struck the record twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation occurred in the euro area as a result of the galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat contributions increased by 88 per cent and soya contributions have reached the highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching as early as last month the black gold almost 100 dollars the barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 percent current to 2.5 percent, instead by 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months about 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
