In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The prevailing conditions of hygiene in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the department physician-head of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
A infection with MRSA has recently been diagnosed in the trauma department of Hospital János.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital early in the year.
A serious car accident wound was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after the infection with MRSA and since then no significant surgical intervention has been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in her body.
Until December 10 of this year we have registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents - said Karolina Böröcz, department physician- chief of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded, and no information is available.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, methicillin-oxacillin-resistant.
One third of humans carry in their nose Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, tonsilitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is applied excessively or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that usually react well to antibiotics become bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and quickly infect in inadequate hospital conditions.
They may cause serious hospital infections, such as injuries or septicemia first of all to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to elderly or to persons with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
You should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where his presence is not examined.
Antibiotics resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff care for them in rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," Tibor Nyulasi said.
Patients hospitalized are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not even possible to prevent infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA's hospital infections in most cases, however, the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come out in public light when the already visible MRSA infections occur in the patient - said the department chief-doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union strongly commends the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples is even less common in the case of travelling patients or in the primary care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saving with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, but also in this sense there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA was infected by the transmission of drops and direct contact between individuals, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated for at least 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately you can also experience - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals of less favourable economic situation saves with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In Karolina Böröcz's view, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer such infections are recorded or the infection of the pathogen may be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
Treatment of the infection with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program seems to have success, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
