EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three limit credit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total amount of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and the environment infrastructure as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget for projects to transport and protect the environment, which will be carried out from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement of a value of EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The loan contract of EUR 150 million is also used to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this target in Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later, by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the project of innovations and research at the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalises with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will return to the subject which, if necessary or not to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in line with the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging fees for maintaining the credit at the disposal of the debtor.
