Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the Minister of the Environment and Hydrology of Gábor Fodor, meetings at the expert level will be completed on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official opening will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries in the world are discussing the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Discussions on the particular issue between developing and industrialised countries are currently taking place.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to reach agreement that compared with the 1990 situation, by 2020 the emissions of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent by the year 2020.
Another important theme of the conference is that if industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are prepared to provide material and technological assistance to countries that need it.
A further agreement was reached on aid for developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes "Piac est Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its emissions of greenhouse gases by 20 percent to 2020, with respect to the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the "after 2012 agreement" will be signed, and is prepared to commit to decreasing by even 30 percent if the other major developed regions in the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within which the 15 EU Member States then committed to reaching 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent over the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet - notes the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
It is a great deal of what is at stake in Bali, since within two years the international long-term climate policy agreement will have to be signed, because if not, it is sure that its entry into force would be postponed by after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its latest report by the IPCC, an international scientific association of the United Nations that deals with climate change, which obtained the Nobel Peace Prize.
As a result, emissions reduction would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the average temperature of the earth could not be prevented, which according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: the special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These tapes made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general Kandahar operations body, then sent to London to be loaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
It is already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been loaded in this way to the Internet and its "channel" has already been seen by over 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of actions in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the British Community (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence, they also served to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda almost costs nothing compared to conventional recruiting television spots - the BBC told defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, inevitably they have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans set up a video game
The army is also concerned at the fact that, in addition to the tapes carefully edited and censored, there are also amateur videos in the distributor, such as about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers speak as much as possible of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battle camps of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with video games of shooting, which can be downloaded for free, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can be put directly instead of the soldiers.
