A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million file documents, stored on 27 km of shelves at Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not available here only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e., individually and nominally, at the request of an old victim or his/her possessor.
The 11 States responsible for their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to the researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratifying this agreement by all States has been concluded, openness has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Access by historians to Bad Arolsen will allow search " particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers ", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, had opposed the opening of these nominating documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the peasants deported or subjected to compulsory work and, where appropriate, to provide them with proof of their detention in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees treat tens of thousands of individual petitions.
For a part of the scientific community, however, access to Bad Arolsen is a limited interest.
" There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the University of Berlin in 2006.
