Congress approves the transposition of Mifid, which entered into force 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated into the draft Senate, the Government has submitted to the public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and Senators to negotiate and consent to the best regulation in order to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activity of entities for markets to function efficiently.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, entails the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (NCMV) and promotes cooperation between the various European Union supervisors.
The new legislation will provide financial advisory services to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial service firm (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio managers.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the implementation of operations on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are complemented by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment service companies to disclose information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all the operations they perform, in order to facilitate the monitoring by the CNMV.
In its passage through the Congressional Economy Commission, several amendments were incorporated, including the fact that debt titulated is considered as a "complex" financial instrument given its high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated with the debt of high-risk U.S. mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delineate the functions that graduates can develop in economics and business 30 years after the real decree delimiting professional functions reserved for economists was adopted in 1977.
For its part, the Senate incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as that of the mediator, who will work for others, will not require the authorization of CNMV and will be able to provide its product marketing and customer collection services to different investment firms at the same time.
