Venus: twin brother from Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most like the Earth, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and somolins in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on the Earth.
For three decades now, researchers have suspected that lightning could exist in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new tests: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays are silent at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of the life of Urey-Miller, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, had given birth to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not like this: if there was one day there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface reign temperatures of 500°C, oscillating so that temperatures under zero can be reached.
"Perhaps Venus is a "diabolic" twin of Earth, but it remains a twin," said Russell.
The main objective of the mission "Venus Express" is to answer the question why Venus, so much like the Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step in the investigation of Venus.
The latest results of the research to be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to researchers, not only emphasize Venus' uniqueness in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with the Earth than we had expected," reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon recalls the wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost so large.
This planet also called a blue star or evening star orbits around the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar is not much like Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed in the same conditions.
On the two planets water had been agglomerated on Earth that remained in the oceans, but on Venus it disounded in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, in Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
